{
  "_comment": "Kitsoki concept pitch. Leads with control inversion and the proofs a coding-agent skeptic can't dismiss: the runtime overrules the model mid-call, ~78% of turns never call the LLM, edits hot-reload and replay byte-for-byte as tests, and the workflow runs where work already lives. After the one-prompt strawman it credits the Cherny loop (loop engineering: a gated, budgeted agent loop that converges) and argues phases-not-prompts is that idea generalized into a composable graph. The phases arc then shows the gates routing review failures back to implement, plan, or reproduce \u2014 and that this can loop multiple times.",
