    {
      "type": "diagram-svg",
      "title": "The Cherny loop",
      "panels": [
        {
          "label": "",
          "viewBox": "0 0 1180 760",
          "nodes": [
            {
              "id": "goal",
              "label": "goal",
              "sub": "+ a gate that can prove it",
              "x": 70,
              "y": 20,
              "w": 520,
              "h": 120
            },
            {
              "id": "maker",
              "label": "maker",
              "sub": "smallest change toward the goal",
              "lines": [
                "fed the last gate failure"
              ],
              "x": 70,
              "y": 200,
              "w": 520,
              "h": 160,
              "style": "primary"
            },
            {
              "id": "gate",
              "label": "gate \u00b7 checker",
              "sub": "script (exit 0) or agent",
              "lines": [
                "pass = goal actually met"
              ],
              "x": 70,
              "y": 420,
              "w": 520,
              "h": 160
            },
            {
              "id": "done",
              "label": "done",
              "sub": "goal met \u2014 or budget ceiling hit",
              "x": 70,
              "y": 640,
              "w": 520,
              "h": 100
            }
          ],
          "edges": [
            {
              "from": "goal",
              "to": "maker"
            },
            {
              "from": "maker",
              "to": "gate",
              "label": "check"
            },
            {
              "from": "gate",
              "to": "done",
              "label": "\u2713 pass"
            },
            {
              "from": "gate",
              "to": "maker",
              "style": "back",
              "bus": 700,
              "lift": 0,
              "label": "fail \u00b7 feed the reason forward"
            }
          ]
        }
      ],
      "caption": "Loop engineering, after Boris Cherny: an agent iterates toward a goal until a gate proves it's actually met \u2014 or a budget ceiling stops it. Launch it once; it converges on its own.",
      "hold": 240,
      "narration": "This is loop engineering \u2014 what Boris Cherny calls a loop. Instead of prompting an agent, you write the loop that prompts it: a maker makes the smallest change, a gate proves whether the goal is actually met, and a budget keeps it from running forever. Each failure feeds the next iteration, so it converges. You launch it once and watch it finish.",
      "instant": true
    },
    {
      "type": "narrative",
      "eyebrow": "Loop engineering, generalized",
      "body": "Kitsoki is the same idea \u2014 a graph of these loops.",
      "lede": "A Cherny loop solves one goal with one gate and one budget. Kitsoki makes every phase its own gated, budgeted loop and composes them \u2014 so the approach is more structured, scalable, repeatable, composable, extendable, traceable, and deterministic wherever a script can replace the model.",
      "hold": 210,
      "narration": "Kitsoki takes the same idea and generalizes it. A single Cherny loop solves one goal. Kitsoki makes every phase its own gated, budgeted loop, then composes them into a graph you can extend \u2014 more structured, scalable, repeatable, composable, extendable, traceable, and deterministic. That's phases, not prompts."
    },
